07324nam a22009855i 9783110688436DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106884367 a10.1515/97831106884362doi  a(DE-B1597)541546  a(OCoLC)1348490824  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0160002bisacsh00aNietzsche and the Politics of Difference /ced. by Andrea Rehberg, Ashley Woodward. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (343 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 Politics and Difference -- tNietzsche, Rancière and the Disputation of Politics -- tComposing Time: Stiegler on Nietzsche, Nihilism and a Possible Future -- tPart 2 Politics and Identity -- tNietzsche’s Diagnosis of Socrates in The Birth of Tragedy: Voyeurism and the Denigration of Difference -- tEcce Homo – Notes on Duplicates: The Great Politics of the Self -- tVoluntary Submission and the ʻPolitics of Truth’: Nietzsche and Foucault on the Danger of the Fully Normalised ‘Last Human’ -- tTowards Immanence – A Nietzschean Trajectory -- tPart 3 Nietzsche and Deleuze on a New Politics -- tEchoes of a New Politics: Deleuze’s Nietzsche and the Political -- tThe Topology of Difference: Deleuze’s Nietzsche in his Politics of Folded Spaces and Subjects -- tFake or Just Stupid? – Post-Truth Politics, Nihilism and the Politics of Difference in Light of Deleuze’s Nietzsche and Philosophy -- tThe Idiot: Deleuze’s Nietzsche for a Politics of Difference -- tPart 4 The Politics of the Agon -- tDisparate Conceptions of the Agon: Nietzsche and Agonistic Democracy -- tAgonal Human Rights: A Re-evaluation of Democracy Through Nietzsche’s Physio-Psychology of Will to Power -- tPart 5 Plurality, Affirmation, Immanence -- tNietzsche and a Politics of Difference: Realising the Forces in the Margins -- tNietzsche, Foucault and the Politics of the Ascetic Ideal -- tThe Quandary of Identity and the Prospective Appearance of Free Spirits in our Globalising Age -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of Nietzsche’s use of political theory has a long and vexed history. The contributors of this book re-situate debates around the notion of difference, in relation to historical and scholarly concerns, but with a view to the current political context. Given that today we are faced with a host of political challenges of domination and resistance, the question raised in this volume is how Nietzsche helps us to think through and to address some of the problems. The authors also discuss how his writings complicate our desire for swift solutions to seemingly intractable problems: how to resist slavishness in thought and action, how to maintain hard-won civil liberties and rights in the face of encroaching hegemonic discourses, practices and forces, or how to counteract global environmental degradation, in short, how to oppose ‘totalitarian’ movements of homogenization, universalization, equalization, and instead to affirm, both politically and ontologically, a culture of difference.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aNietzsche, Friedrich. 4aPolitik der Differenz. 4aPolitische Theorie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aNietzsche, Friedrich.  aidentity.  apolitics of difference.1 aBaier, Glen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColony, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorall, Niklas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellens, Sven, econtributor.4ctb4htt